data.Name: Eonothem
data.Description: In stratigraphy and geology, an eonothem is the totality of rock strata laid down in the stratigraphic record deposited during a certain eon of the continuous geologic timescale.

data.Name: Erathem
data.Description: In stratigraphy, paleontology, geology, and geobiology an erathem is the total stratigraphic unit deposited during a certain corresponding span of time during an era in the geologic timescale.

data.Name: System
data.Description: A system in stratigraphy is a unit of rock layers that were laid down together within the same corresponding geological period. The associated period is a chronological time unit, a part of the geological time scale, while the system is a unit of chronostratigraphy. Systems are unrelated to lithostratigraphy, which subdivides rock layers on their lithology. Systems are subdivisions of erathems and are themselves divided into series and stages.

data.Name: Series
data.Description: Series are subdivisions of rock layers based on the age of the rock and formally defined by international conventions of the geological timescale. A series is therefore a sequence of strata defining a chronostratigraphic unit. Series are subdivisions of systems and are themselves divided into stages.

data.Name: Stage
data.Description: In chronostratigraphy, a stage is a succession of rock strata laid down in a single age on the geologic timescale, which usually represents millions of years of deposition. A given stage of rock and the corresponding age of time will by convention have the same name, and the same boundaries.

data.Name: Chronozone
data.Description: A chronozone or chron is a unit in chronostratigraphy, defined by events such as geomagnetic reversals (magnetozones), or based on the presence of specific fossils (biozone or biochronozone). According to the International Commission on Stratigraphy, the term "chronozone" refers to the rocks formed during a particular time period, while "chron" refers to that time period

data.Name: Unknown
data.Description: The reference value to be used for unknown Chronostratigraphic StratigraphicColumnRankUnitType values.

data.Name: Group
data.Description: A group is a lithostratigraphic unit, a part of the geologic record preserved in rock strata. Groups are generally divided into individual formations. Groups may sometimes be combined into supergroups.

data.Name: Formation
data.Description: The fundamental unit of lithostratigraphy. A body of rock that is sufficiently distinctive and continuous that it can be mapped. In stratigraphy, a formation is a body of strata of predominantly one type or combination of types; multiple formations form groups, and subdivisions of formations are members.

data.Name: Member
data.Description: A subdivision of a formation (see Lithostratigraphic.Formation)

data.Name: Unknown
data.Description: The reference value to be used for unknown Lithostratigraphic StratigraphicColumnRankUnitType values.

data.Name: Unknown
data.Description: The reference value to be used for unknown Biostratigraphic StratigraphicColumnRankUnitType values.

data.Name: Biozone
data.Description: A stratigraphic interval or rock layer characterized by a distinctive assemblage of fossils. It is defined by the presence of one or more species of fossils that are used to identify and correlate rocks across different regions

data.Name: Biosubzone
data.Description: A further subdivision of a biozone

data.Name: Unknown
data.Description: The reference value to be used for unknown Chemostratigraphic StratigraphicColumnRankUnitType values.

data.Name: Chemozone
data.Description: A stratigraphic interval defined by a distinctive chemical property or signature

data.Name: Chemosubzone
data.Description: A subdivision of a chemozone

data.Name: Unknown
data.Description: The reference value to be used for unknown Magnetostratigraphic StratigraphicColumnRankUnitType values.

data.Name: Magnetochron
data.Description: A stratigraphic interval defined by a period of consistent polarity of the earth's magnetic field

data.Name: Unknown
data.Description: The reference value to be used for unknown Sequencestratigraphic StratigraphicColumnRankUnitType values.

data.Name: Sequence
data.Description: In sequence stratigraphy, a sequence is a package of genetically related sedimentary strata bounded by unconformities, surfaces of erosion, or correlative conformity surfaces. Sequences are defined by changes in depositional environment and sedimentation rates and are characterized by distinctive stacking patterns of sedimentary rocks. The boundaries between sequences, also known as sequence boundaries, are typically defined by abrupt changes in lithology, sedimentary structures, or fossil assemblages.

data.Name: Systemstract
data.Description: DEPRECATED: Please use Code="Sequencestratigraphic.LowstandSystemsTract" with Name="Lowstand Systems Tract" instead. In sequence stratigraphy, a systems tract is a subdivision of a sequence that is defined by the depositional setting and the pattern of sediment accumulation within the sequence. Systems tracts represent specific phases of sedimentation within a sequence and are bounded by surfaces of sequence stratigraphic significance, such as sequence boundaries or maximum flooding surfaces.

data.Name: Parasequence
data.Description: In sequence stratigraphy, a parasequence is a subdivision of a systems tract that is bounded by surfaces of marine erosion or non-deposition and represents a relatively small-scale unit of sedimentation. Parasequences are characterized by a distinctive pattern of sediment accumulation and reflect changes in depositional setting and sediment supply.

data.Name: Lowstand Systems Tract
data.Description: DEPRECATED: Please use Code="Sequencestratigraphic.LowstandSystemsTract" with Name="Lowstand Systems Tract" instead. A lowstand systems tract (LST) is a term to describe a specific phase of sediment deposition within a stratigraphic sequence. It represents a period of relative sea-level fall or a decrease in water depth in a sedimentary basin.

data.Name: Transgressive SystemsTract
data.Description: DEPRECATED: Please use Code="Sequencestratigraphic.TransgressiveSystemsTract" with Name="Transgressive Systems Tract" instead. A transgressive systems tract (TST) is a term to describe a specific phase of sediment deposition within a stratigraphic sequence. It represents a period of relative sea-level rise or an increase in water depth in a sedimentary basin.

data.Name: Highstand Systems Tract
data.Description: DEPRECATED: Please use Code="Sequencestratigraphic.HighstandSystemsTract" with Name="Highstand Systems Tract" instead. A highstand systems tract (HST) is a term to describe a specific phase of sediment deposition within a stratigraphic sequence. It represents a period of relative sea-level stability in which sediment supply is greater than accommodation space creation resulting in sediment progradation

data.Name: SuperEonothem
data.Description: In stratigraphy and geology, a supereonothem is a chronostratigraphic rank, group of successive eonothems

data.Description: In stratigraphy and geology, a subseries is a chronostratigraphic unit ranking immediately above stages and below a series

data.Name: Laminae
data.Description: A lamina is defined as the smallest megascopic layer in a sedimentary succession that is relatively uniform in texture and composition.

data.Name: Laminae Set
data.Description: A lamina set is defined as one lamina or a group of laminae that are arranged in a specific structure or geometry that can be distinguished from adjacent strata by the thickness, grain size, geometry, or termination surfaces of the comprising laminae.

data.Name: Bed
data.Description: A bed is defined as a relatively conformable set of genetically-related laminae or lamina sets that are bounded by bedding surfaces that reveal the principal rock layering or bedding.

data.Name: Bedset
data.Description: Two or more superposed beds characterized by similar composition, texture, and/or sedimentary structures.

data.Name: Storey
data.Description: One or more superposed Bed Sets, arranged in a rhythmic or systematic fashion, with upper and lower bounding surfaces (Storey Boundaries) that are abrupt and continuous, and at which all Bed Set boundaries terminate by onlap, downlap, toplap or truncation.

data.Name: Storey Set
data.Description: One or more superposed Storeys, arranged in a rhythmic or systematic fashion, with upper and lower bounding surfaces (Storey Set Boundaries) that are abrupt and continuous, and at which all Storey boundaries terminate by onlap, downlap, toplap or truncation.

data.Name: Channel
data.Description: One or more superposed Storeys or Storey Sets, arranged in a rhythmic or systematic fashion, with upper and lower bounding surfaces (Storey Set Boundaries) that are abrupt and continuous, and at which boundaries terminate by onlap, downlap, toplap or truncation.

data.Name: Complex
data.Description: One or more juxtaposed Storey Sets, or bundles of Storey Sets, arranged in one or more rhythmic or systematic patterns, with upper and lower bounding surfaces (Complex Boundaries) that are abrupt, continuous, and across which there is a major shift in lithofacies associations, and reorganization of depositional map patterns.

data.Name: Complex Set
data.Description: One or more genetically-related Complexes, or groups of Complexes, with upper and lower bounding surfaces (Complex Set Boundaries) that are regionally extensive, and across which there is a significant change in grain size, lithology, stacking patterns, and/or depositional map patterns.

data.Name: Sequence Set
data.Description: A relatively conformable succession of genetically-related sequences characterized by aggradational, progradational, or retrogradational stacking patterns.

data.Name: Composite Sequence
data.Description: A relatively conformable succession of genetically-related Sequence Sets characterized by a systematic and repetitive succession of stacking patterns.

data.Name: Composite Sequence Set
data.Description: A relatively conformable succession of genetically-related composite sequences characterized by a systematic and repetitive succession of stacking patterns.

data.Name: Super Sequence
data.Description: The tectonic grouping at a larger scale
